{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"mimetype":"text/x-r-source","name":"R","pygments_lexer":"r","version":"3.6.0","file_extension":".r","codemirror_mode":"r"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This is an analysis report for a fictional company named Cyclistic, given by Google Data Analytics Certificate course 8 as a Capstone project.\n\n# Introduction\n## About the company\nIn 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime. Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments.One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes,and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.\n\n## My Role\nI am a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the company’s future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, my team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, my team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.\n\n## Business Task\nTo find insights that helps in understanding the difference between casual members and annual members, to create effective marketing strategy, in order to convert casual members into annual members.\n      \n## Data Sources used\nI downloaded the Cyclistic’s historical trip data to analyze and identify trends.Download the previous 12 months of Cyclistic trip data [here](https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html). The data has been made available by Motivate International Inc. under this [license](https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement).\n\n## Process\nI decided to use R for analysis. After downloading the data as zip files i unzipped them and stored into a folder. Then I downloaded the r studio as I thought doing this project on cloud would not handle that much computing. After downloading and installing r studio, I installed the necessary packages, like readr, tidyverse,plyr etc.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library('readr')\nlibrary('tidyverse')\nlibrary('plyr')   ","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Loading all 12 month data ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"files1=list.files(path=\"C:\\\\Users\\\\Lenovo\\\\Downloads\\\\tripdata\\\\\" , pattern=\".csv\", full.names=TRUE)\ncombined_csv= ldply(files1, read_csv)\nfiles2=list.files(path=\"C:\\\\Users\\\\Lenovo\\\\Downloads\\\\tripdata2\\\\\" , pattern=\".csv\", full.names=TRUE)\ncombined_csv2= ldply(files2, read_csv)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Combining all the files to get 12-month view","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df01<- rbind(combined_csv,combined_csv2)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Cleaning and formatting data suitable to analysis\n\nRemoving unwanted columns not needed for this analysis","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df02<- cyclistic_df01 %>% \nselect(-c(ride_id,start_station_id,start_lat,start_lng,end_station_id,end_lat,end_lng))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Calculating difference between started_at and ended_at as 'ride_length', adding it as column in data frame to understand duration of trips for casual and members","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df02$ride_length<-difftime(Cyclistic_df02$ended_at,Cyclistic_df02$started_at, units = 'mins')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Removing na values","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df02<-cyclistic_df02 %>% distinct()","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Converting ride_length datatype character to numeric","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df01$ride_length<-as.numeric(as.character(cyclistic_df01$ride_length))\nis.numeric(cyclistic_df01$ride_length)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Removing negative and values containing 0 and negative value in ride_length","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03<-cyclistic_df02\ncyclistic_df03<-cyclistic_df03[!(cyclistic_df03$ride_length<=0),]","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Adding day_of_week column for calculation","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03$day_of_week <- wday(cyclistic_df03$started_at)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Adding month, year using format on date for calculations","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":" cyclistic_df03$month <- format(as.Date(data_12_months_v2$date), \"%m\")\ncyclistic_df03$day <- format(as.Date(data_12_months_v2$date), \"%d\")\ncyclistic_df03$year <- format(as.Date(data_12_months_v2$date), \"%Y\")\ncyclistic_df03$day_of_week <- format(as.Date(data_12_months_v2$date), \"%A\")","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"by using \"%A\" I converted day of week from numeric to text.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Analyzing and Visualizing data\n\nPlotting day_of_week, count of trips done by summarizing using dplyr and member casual","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03 %>%\ngroup_by(day_of_week,member_casual) %>%\ndplyr::summarize(count_trips=n()) %>%\nggplot()+geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=day_of_week,y=count_trips,colour=member_casual,\n                              fill=member_casual),stat='identity',position = 'dodge')+\ntheme_update()+labs(title='Number of Rides Per Week',subtitle='Casual vs.Member',\n                    x='day_of_week',y='Count of Trips')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![Number of rides per week](attachment:e1459fc4-6ab5-495f-aa57-d0f1f5b8ae55.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"e1459fc4-6ab5-495f-aa57-d0f1f5b8ae55.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Converting month from numeric to text","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03$month<-format(as.Date(cyclistic_df03$date),\"%b\")","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Plotting month, count of trips,member casual","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03 %>%\ngroup_by(month,member_casual) %>%\ndplyr::summarize(count_trips=n()) %>%\nggplot()+geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=month,y=count_trips,colour=member_casual,\n                              fill=member_casual),stat='identity',position = 'dodge')+\ntheme_update()+labs(title='Number of Rides Per Month',subtitle='Casual vs.Member',\n                    x='Month',y='Count of Trips')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![Number of Rides Per Month](attachment:6fa0f458-ff3d-454b-a7df-9fbd82661f36.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"6fa0f458-ff3d-454b-a7df-9fbd82661f36.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Plotting rideable_type, count of trips, member_casual","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03 %>%\ngroup_by(month,member_casual) %>%\ndplyr::summarize(count_trips=n()) %>%\nggplot()+geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=rideable_type,y=count_trips,colour=member_casual,\n                              fill=member_casual),stat='identity',position = 'dodge')+\ntheme_update()+labs(title='Popular Bikes',subtitle='Casual vs.Member',\n                    x='Rideable_type',y='Count of Trips')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![Popular Bikes](attachment:19e00295-f82d-4fb5-97d5-d29a1cc13f4d.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"19e00295-f82d-4fb5-97d5-d29a1cc13f4d.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Plotting start_station_name, count of trips, member_casual, filtered by casual only","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df03<-cyclistic_df04\ncyclistic_df04 %>%\ngroup_by(member_casual, start_station_name)  %>%\ndplyr::summarize(count_trips=n())  %>%\nfilter(start_station_name!=\"\",member_casual=='casual') %>%\narrange(desc(count_trips)) %>%\nhead(10) %>%\nggplot()+geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=start_station_name,y=count_trips,\n                              fill=member_casual),stat='identity')+\ntheme_update(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 270))+\nlabs(title='Popular Start Stations',subtitle='For Casual')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![Popular Start Stations](attachment:d48e7058-09fa-4a05-a9ca-ccb6629ba1e3.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"d48e7058-09fa-4a05-a9ca-ccb6629ba1e3.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Plotting start_station_name, count of trips, member_casual, filtered by member only","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cyclistic_df04 %>%\ngroup_by(member_casual, start_station_name)  %>%\ndplyr::summarize(count_trips=n())  %>%\nfilter(start_station_name!=\"\",member_casual=='member') %>%\narrange(desc(count_trips)) %>%\nhead(10) %>%\nggplot()+geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=start_station_name,y=count_trips,\n                              fill=member_casual),stat='identity')+\ntheme_update(axis.text.x=element_text(angle = 270))+\nlabs(title='Popular Start Stations',subtitle='For Member')","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![Popular Start Stations](attachment:ade74b1d-90e6-4ca2-ae6f-e3b1032cd701.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"ade74b1d-90e6-4ca2-ae6f-e3b1032cd701.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### I also created tableau dashboard to practice tableau I learned in Google Data Analytics Certificate.\n### You can see my dashboard [here](https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/learnerrrrrrrr8521/viz/cyclisticdata_16761149414320/Dashboard2)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Recommendations\nWatching the data over the time through 12 months, I would like to recommend to Cyclistic Bike Share Company :-\n\n1. The marketing team is recommended to focus on marketing certain special attractions on Saturday and Sundays as those are the days casuals like to use their cycles a lot.\n2. The team can also focus on creating offers or discounts through the months July, August, September. As these months showed the increase in casual members' rides.\n3. Based on visualized data the Team can  increase their marketing in certain cities where casual members are more active, as well for members.\n4. Special discount offers or attention could be given to docked bikes as they are most popular between both casuals and members.\n\n\n## References\n\nFor r code of my analysis I referred to this this [report](https://www.kaggle.com/code/itamargn/cyclistic-case-study/report)","metadata":{}}]}